docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:135:- *106 ms ON max is a single-frame transient (similar pattern to 
outdoor OFF outliers — not DPVS-related)
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:147:| Open outdoor (few effective occluders) | **Net cost** | DPVS 
pays the query cost per frame without finding much to skip. Cost grows with object count. |
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:148:| Closed indoor cell (many intra-cell occluders) | **Net 
savings** | Tight space with chairs/tables/walls/NPC clusters; DPVS skips substantial draw work. 
Savings shrink in chaotic moving scenes (more recomputation) but stay positive. |
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:151:- Outdoor: DPVS cost increases (940 µs sparse → 1,592 µs dense); 
savings stay near zero → bigger net loss.
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:152:- Indoor: DPVS savings shrink (940 µs sparse → 654 µs dense) but 
stay net positive → net gain still present, magnitude smaller in moving scenes.
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:154:The crossover happens because outdoor scenes simply lack the 
occluder density that makes DPVS pay off. The cantina at 27.56 ms with DPVS ON is the fastest frame 
time we measured anywhere — better than even outdoor with DPVS off — because indoor cells have a 
fundamentally smaller world to draw, and DPVS optimally exploits that.
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:159:- **D-10 threshold:** OFF wins on both median AND p95 → 
`remove`. Outdoor scenes: yes for all three. Indoor scene: ON wins on both → `keep`.
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:160:- **D-11 inconclusive-defaults-to-keep:** Outdoor magnitudes 
(3.3-9.1%) are well above noise floor; indoor magnitude (2.2%) was robustness-checked with a second 
capture session at 4× higher density and a different camera anchor — same direction, same magnitude. 
Not inconclusive on either side.
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:196:This verdict is valid for the **D3D9 renderer only.** Phase 11's 
D3D11 plugin changes draw-call cost; DPVS occlusion savings depend on draw-call cost; the verdict 
could flip under D3D11 — particularly for the outdoor scenes where DPVS is currently net-negative by 
a margin proportional to per-object draw cost.
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:201:- Outdoor verdict stays `remove`: D3D11's faster draw call cost 
reduces but doesn't reverse the DPVS overhead. Likely.
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:202:- Outdoor verdict flips to `keep`: D3D11 makes draws so cheap 
that DPVS overhead dominates. Possible but unlikely given DPVS's per-frame query cost is 
GPU-independent.
docs\recon\10-dpvs-profiling.md:203:- Indoor verdict stays `keep`: Indoor savings come from skipping 
geometry-dense interior draws; D3D11 doesn't change that. Very likely.
