.planning/research\CONSULT-25-codex.clean.txt:22:I mostly agree with the hazard characterization, 
but I’d phrase it more narrowly: the evidence shows the shared `NO_OVERWRITE` ring contract is 
invalid for this workload. It may be literal CPU overwrite of an in-flight region, or it may be 
driver-side range/rename bookkeeping getting defeated by the shared ring plus deferred draws. Either 
way, the fix is the same: remove soft skin from the shared append/no-overwrite allocator.
.planning/research\CONSULT-19-vs-fallback-interior-asm.md:6:Building INTERIORS (POB cells: 
walls/floor/ceiling) and the open-world SKY do not render under D3D11; the legacy D3D9 path (`gl05`) 
renders them fine. RenderDoc + targeted instrumentation pinned it:
.planning/research\CONSULT-19-vs-fallback-interior-asm.md:8:- Named culprits: `stco_cantina_wall_*`, 
`intr_{hotel,tech,library,medical,commerce,combat}_*`, `despot_*`, `spaceport_*`, 
`frn_tatt_wall_*_cantina`, `glss_cantina_window`, `gradient_sky`, etc. — i.e. the entire 
interior/structural/sky surface set.
.planning/research\CONSULT-19-vs-fallback-interior-asm.md:31:A recommended design (generic fallback 
VS vs per-format vs author-HLSL) with: the exact injection point (file:line), the input/output 
signature for the fallback VS, the WVP cbuffer source, how it chains to the existing PS fallback, 
the top 3 pitfalls + how to detect each, and a cheap first verification (e.g., "interior walls 
render textured-passthrough in RenderDoc; check draw N's bound VS = fallback"). If author-HLSL is 
better, say why and estimate scope.
.planning/research\CONSULT-19-vs-fallback-interior-asm-SYNTHESIS.md:15:1. **Static-world** — 
